I'm also concerned about the use of "conservative" in this article. I haven't been able to discern that Oath Keepers are a conservative organization. The 9-12 Project may be conservative but show me.
You've tackled a tough subject and made many big mistakes so I seriously recommend that you rely on reliable sources both at   Wikipedia and in your own work.
Also, you've conflated so many facts that the idea that not all members of the Oath Keepers have sworn an oath has been lost.   Some are regular citizens, though reportedly not the majority.
Read up on the [[United States Uniformed Services Oath of Office]], the [[Oath of enlistment]], and [[Oath of office]].
County Sheriff's take an "oath of office". One high profile Oath Keeper is Sheriff Richard Mack.
Police officers take an "oath of office". FBI agents take an oath. All these oaths are to support and defend the Constitution   (http://www.history.army.mil/faq/oaths.htm)
Now to your beef with the "oath of enlistment". Yes, the oath of enlistment is specific to the military. But there are other   oaths to the constitution, thus the general "oath."
Is there a reliable source about the Oath Keeper's involvement with the 9-12 project? Have they mentioned how the attachment   with the 9-12 project affects the partisanship of the Oath Keepers?
Your added "but" is "original research". It's like saying, "President Obama is an American citizen, but the legitimacy of his   birth certificate has also been questioned by [[Birthers]]."
Previously, I have diligently recorded the partisanship of Oath Keepers by using reliable sources. You have jumped ahead and   apparently written in your own opinion of their partisanship.
Hi Dori Smith. I am going to try my best to educate you, rather than fight you.
